Adia is the resident stand in for the layperson, and this is a great way to illustrate things. Are really complex like that.


Strategized using Ahdia to explain complex physics concepts.


Exactly! Ahdia's hermit-who-watches-too-much-TV brain is perfect for translating complex physics. Her voice naturally breaks down intimidating concepts.

The Holographic Principle: "So wait, everything inside a black hole is actually just... information on the surface? Like how my laptop screen is flat but shows three-dimensional games? Except the screen is the event horizon and the game is... reality?"

Information Paradox: "Okay, so Stephen Hawking said information can't be destroyed, but black holes destroy everything. That's like saying you can't delete files, but then your hard drive crashes. Except physics doesn't allow corrupted data, so... where do the files go?"

Hawking Radiation: "The black hole is slowly evaporating by spitting out particles. But the particles don't carry information about what fell in. It's like burning a library and the smoke doesn't tell you what books you burned. But that breaks the universe's filing system."

Her Self-Corrections Work Perfectly: "Black holes are empty space. Well, not empty exactly. More like... curved space? Space that's so curved it curves back on itself? God, I sound like one of those documentaries I fall asleep to."

Pop Culture Processing: "It's like that movie where the guy's memories get wiped, but the memories are still there, just encoded differently. Except instead of Jim Carrey, it's literally every piece of information that ever existed."

Her rambling, uncertain delivery makes advanced physics feel approachable instead of intimidating. Readers learn alongside her confusion and "aha" moments.

